🔥 🔹 RiskPolicy TYPE kya hota hai?
👉 Type batata hai policy kis tarah ka check karegi.
✅ Common Types (SailPoint me):-
1. 🔹 SOD (Segregation of Duties):-
👉 Conflict detect karta hai (2 dangerous access ek sath)
Example:-
User ke paas:-
- Payment Create
- Payment Approve ❌
👉 Ye violation hai

2. 🔹 Activity:-
👉 User ke actions/activity pe based
Example:-
User ne 10 baar login fail kiya

3. 🔹 Identity:-
👉 Identity attributes pe check
Example:-
Department = Finance AND Role = Admin

4. 🔹 Account:-
👉 Account level check (Link level)
Example:-
AD account disabled nahi hai but user inactive hai

5. 🔹 Entitlement:-
👉 Access/group level check
Example:-
User ke paas "Admin Group" hai

6. 🔹 Role:-
👉 Role based violation
Example:-
2 high-risk roles ek sath assign.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🔥 🔹 RiskPolicy STATE kya hota hai?
👉 State batata hai policy ka current status kya hai.
✅ Common States:-
1. 🔹 Active:-
👉 Policy chal rahi hai (enabled)
Violations detect honge ✅

2. 🔹 Inactive:-
👉 Policy band hai
Koi violation check nahi hoga ❌

3. 🔹 Draft:-
👉 Policy abhi ban rahi hai (testing phase)
Final nahi hai

4. 🔹 Deprecated:-
👉 Old policy (use nahi karna)
Replace ho chuki hai

5. 🔹 Testing (kabhi-kabhi custom):-
👉 Sirf testing ke liye
Production me use nahi hoti

⚡ Short me:-
👉 State = policy chal rahi hai ya nahi

🔥 Real Example:-
Policy Name: Finance SoD
Type  = SOD
State = Active
👉 Matlab:-
👉 Finance conflict detect karegi aur abhi active hai.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🔥 🔹 1. getId() / setId(String id):-
👉 Policy ka unique ID set aur get karta hai
✅ Code:-
Policy policy = new Policy();
policy.setId("RP001");
System.out.println(policy.getId());
✅ Output:-
RP001

🔥 🔹 2. getName() / setName(String name):-
👉 Policy ka naam (name) set/get karta hai
✅ Code:-
policy.setName("Finance SoD Policy");
System.out.println(policy.getName());
✅ Output:-
Finance SoD Policy

🔥 🔹 3. getDescription() / setDescription(String description):-
👉 Policy ka detail description store karta hai
✅ Code:-
policy.setDescription("This policy checks finance conflicts");
System.out.println(policy.getDescription());
✅ Output:-
This policy checks finance conflicts

🔥 🔹 4. getType() / setType(String type):-
👉 Policy kis type ki hai (SOD, Entitlement, Role, etc.)
✅ Code:-
policy.setType("SOD");
System.out.println(policy.getType());
✅ Output:-
SOD

🔥 🔹 5. getState() / setState(String state):-
👉 Policy ka status (Active, Inactive, Draft)
✅ Code:-
policy.setState("Active");
System.out.println(policy.getState());
✅ Output:-
Active

🔥 🔹 6. isActive() / setActive(boolean active):-
👉 Boolean form me batata hai policy ON hai ya OFF
✅ Code:-
policy.setActive(true);
System.out.println(policy.isActive());
✅ Output:-
true
--------------------------------------------------------------------------
⚡ Combined Example (Full Flow):-
Policy policy = new Policy();

policy.setId("RP001");
policy.setName("Finance SoD Policy");
policy.setDescription("Checks conflicting access");
policy.setType("SOD");
policy.setState("Active");
policy.setActive(true);

System.out.println(policy.getId());
System.out.println(policy.getName());
System.out.println(policy.getDescription());
System.out.println(policy.getType());
System.out.println(policy.getState());
System.out.println(policy.isActive());
✅ Final Output:-
RP001
Finance SoD Policy
Checks conflicting access
SOD
Active
true
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🔥 🔹 getOwner() / setOwner(Identity owner) kya hai?
👉 Ye methods Policy ke owner ko set aur get karte hain.
🧠 Owner ka matlab kya hota hai?
👉 Owner = wo banda (Identity) jo policy ka responsible hai
✔ Policy create kar sakta hai
✔ Policy modify (sudhar) sakta hai
✔ Violation ko review / approve / mitigate karta hai
👉 Sirf creator hi nahi, responsible person hota hai

🔥 🔹 Simple samajh:-
👉 Tumne policy banayi, lekin baad me koi aur admin handle kare
👉 Toh owner change ho sakta hai

🔥 🔹 Code Example:-
Identity admin = new Identity();
admin.setName("Rahul Admin");
Policy policy = new Policy();
policy.setOwner(admin);
System.out.println(policy.getOwner().getName());
✅ Output:-
Rahul Admin
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🔥 🔹 1. getSeverity() / setSeverity(String severity):-
👉 Policy ki danger level batata hai
🎯 Values:-
LOW
MEDIUM
HIGH
CRITICAL

✅ Code:-
policy.setSeverity("HIGH");
System.out.println(policy.getSeverity());
✅ Output:-
HIGH
👉 Matlab: ye policy risky hai 🚨

🔥 🔹 2. getPriority() / setPriority(int priority):-
👉 Policy ki importance order (kaunsi pehle check hogi)
✅ Code:-
policy.setPriority(1);
System.out.println(policy.getPriority());
✅ Output:-
1
👉 Lower number = higher priority
👉 1 = sabse important

🔥 🔹 3. getRiskScore() / setRiskScore(int riskScore):-
👉 Policy violation hone par kitna risk add hoga
✅ Code:-
policy.setRiskScore(50);
System.out.println(policy.getRiskScore());
✅ Output:-
50
👉 Matlab: violation = +50 risk

🔥 🔹 4. getRiskScoreWeight() / setRiskScoreWeight(int weight):-
👉 Risk ka weight (percentage importance)

✅ Code:-
policy.setRiskScoreWeight(20);
System.out.println(policy.getRiskScoreWeight());
✅ Output:-
20

👉 Formula use hota hai:-
Final Risk = (RiskScore * Weight) / 100

👉 Example:-
(50 * 20) / 100 = 10
-----------------------------------------------------------
🔥 🔹 5. getFilter() / setFilter(Filter filter):-
👉 Kis user pe policy apply hogi (condition)

✅ Code:-
Filter filter = new Filter();
filter.setExpression("department == 'Finance'");
policy.setFilter(filter);
System.out.println(policy.getFilter().getExpression());
✅ Output:-
department == 'Finance'

👉 Matlab:-
👉 Ye policy sirf Finance users pe lagegi

🔥 🔥 Full Combined Example:-
Policy policy = new Policy();
policy.setSeverity("CRITICAL");
policy.setPriority(1);
policy.setRiskScore(80);
policy.setRiskScoreWeight(25);
Filter filter = new Filter();
filter.setExpression("department == 'IT'");
policy.setFilter(filter);
System.out.println(policy.getSeverity());
System.out.println(policy.getPriority());
System.out.println(policy.getRiskScore());
System.out.println(policy.getRiskScoreWeight());
System.out.println(policy.getFilter().getExpression());
✅ Final Output:-
CRITICAL
1
80
25
department == 'IT'
------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🔥 🔹 1. getViolationLimit() / setViolationLimit(int limit):-
👉 Violation Limit kya hota hai?
👉 Ye decide karta hai kitni baar violation hone ke baad action lena hai

🧠 Simple samajh:-
limit = 3
👉 Agar user 3 baar policy todta hai
👉 Tab system action lega (alert / block / escalation)

✅ Code:-
policy.setViolationLimit(2);
System.out.println(policy.getViolationLimit());
✅ Output:-
2

🎯 Real Example:-
Policy: Login Failure Policy
Limit = 3
👉 3 baar galat login → account lock 🔒
---------------------------------------------------------------------
🔥 🔹 2. getViolationOwner() / setViolationOwner(Identity owner):-
👉 Violation Owner kya hota hai?
👉 Wo banda jo violation handle karega.
🧠 Difference samajh:-
Type	            Meaning
Owner:------------Policy ka malik
ViolationOwner:---Violation ka handler

✅ Code:-
Identity manager = new Identity();
manager.setName("Security Manager");
policy.setViolationOwner(manager);
System.out.println(policy.getViolationOwner().getName());
✅ Output:-
Security Manager

🎯 Real Example:-
Policy Owner = Admin
Violation Owner = Manager
👉 Admin banata hai
👉 Manager handle karta hai.
---------------------------------------------------------------
🔥 🔹 3. getConstraints() / setConstraints(List constraints)
👉 Constraint kya hota hai?
👉 Policy ke rules / conditions / logic
🧠 Simple samajh:-
👉 Constraint = "kab violation hoga" ka rule
🎯 Example:-
Rule:-
User ke paas Role A AND Role B dono nahi hone chahiye
👉 Ye hi constraint hai
---------------------------------------------------------
✅ Code:-
List<String> constraints = new ArrayList<>();
constraints.add("RoleA AND RoleB not allowed");
policy.setConstraints(constraints);
System.out.println(policy.getConstraints());

✅ Output:-
[RoleA AND RoleB not allowed]
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🔥 🔹 getActions() / setActions(List actions):-
👉 Actions kya hote hain?
👉 Jab policy violation hota hai, tab system kya karega — wo define karta hai

🧠 Simple samajh:-
👉 Constraint = rule
👉 Violation = rule toot gaya
👉 Action = ab kya karna hai

🎯 Common Actions:-
Alert bhejna 📩
Email notify karna
Access revoke karna ❌
Approval bhejna
Account disable karna 🔒
----------------------------------------------------------------
import sailpoint.api.SailPointContext;
import sailpoint.api.SailPointFactory;
import sailpoint.object.Policy;
import sailpoint.object.Identity;

import java.util.*;

public class PolicyActionDemo {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {

        // 🔹 1. Context lena
        SailPointContext context = SailPointFactory.getCurrentContext();

        // 🔹 2. Policy fetch karna
        Policy policy = context.getObjectByName(Policy.class, "Finance SoD Policy");

        // 🔹 3. Actions banana
        List<String> actions = new ArrayList<>();
        actions.add("Send Email");
        actions.add("Revoke Access");

        // 🔹 4. Set actions
        policy.setActions(actions);

        // 🔹 5. Save to DB
        context.saveObject(policy);
        context.commitTransaction();

        System.out.println("Actions added successfully!");
    }
}
✅ Output:
Actions added successfully!
